$ Oracle: DBA_IDENTIFIERS

`dba_identifiers` lists all identifiers that are found in PL/SQL code. This → development/databases/Oracle/installed/data-dictionary view comes in all four variants:
`user_identifiers`, `all_identifiers`, `dba_identifiers` and `cdb_identifiers`.

In order for this view to be populated with the information about identifers, the PL/SQL compilation parameter `psscope_settings` must be set to
`identifiers:all`.

`dba_identifiers` only stores information about basic type names (`variable)`. To determine the exact type of a `variable`, the information from
`usage_context_id` must be used.

code {
select
   --
   -- Identification of the identifer being described
   --
   idt.signature,
   idt.owner,
   idt.name,
   idt.type,
   --
   -- Identification of the PL/SQL object and location where
   -- the identifier being described in the current record
   -- is found:
   --
   idt.object_name,
   idt.object_type,
   idt.line,
   idt.col,
   --
   --
   --
   idt.usage,
   idt.usage_context_id,
   idt.usage_id,
   idt.declared_object_name,
   idt.declared_object_type,
   idt.declared_owner,
   --
   idt.attribute,
   idt.character_set,
   idt.char_used,
   --
   idt.implicit,
   idt.length,
   idt.lower_range,
   idt.null_constraint,


   idt.origin_con_id,
   idt.precision,
   idt.precision2,
   idt.scale,
   idt.sql_builtin,
   idt.upper_range
from
   dba_identifiers idt
code }

sa:

  → development/databases/Oracle/installed/data-dictionary/statements[`dba_statements`]

  The init parameter → development/databases/Oracle/adminstration/init-parameters/plscope_settings[`plscope_settings`]

  → development/databases/Oracle/installed/data-dictionary
